Note for Carly

I changed the code to show differences as percent instead of relative ratios. I’ve subtracted 100% from each simulation to normalize/show the percent different (i.e. a value below 0% means decrease relative to baseline, a value >0% means an increase). You’ll notice that the % change is quite large for a few parameters (e.g. >1000% increase relative to baseline). I think this messes with the visualization as the color scale becomes misleading: basically, it is impossible to discern small changes because the larger values stretch the color palette. We can probably fix this with some clever coding of the color scheme (e.g. use a categorical color scheme) but I thought the relative changes helped circumvent this issue.

Notes

Somehow everything revolves around N:P of 16 even when using average phytoplankton stoichiometry… there seem to be shifts in sensitivity depending on whether N or P limitation prevails.

Much greater changes to baseline in Michaelis-Menten model compared to Droop model –> luxury uptake allows for decoupling of growth and resource supply –> makes model less sensitive? provides buffering capacity?!

Overview

Code to perform sensitivity analysis of algal physiology parameters for Michaelis-Menten and Droop models.

Models are run across TN and TP inflow gradients of 100 - 1000 ug L-1 and 10 - 500 ug L-1 respectively to establish baselines (500 timesteps). Light is held constant at I0 = 400 (umoles m-2 s-1 ). Algal physiology parameters are then varied by +/-10% to evaluate how sensitive C-acquisition is to changes in physiology. Note, that I haven’t performed a sensitivity analysis for umax or KLight as these variables use fundamentally different units than the nutrient/stoichiometry parameters. When included umax appears to be the most influential variable and obscures variation in the other variables. Can easily include umax in the future if folks would like. In addition, sensitivity of cellular N/P to changes in algal physiology is determined for the Droop model.

Sensitivity analysis

Michaelis-Menten models

Increase and decrease algal physiology parameters by +/-10% and store the output. Calculate the change relative to baseline conditions across TN and TP loads.

Code chunk below varies parameters by +10%

Code chunk below varies parameters by -10%
(there is probably a more elegant way to do this but this simple approach works for now.

The code chunk below re-formats the data and merges the simulations with the baseline runs. I’ve calculated the relative change from the simulation to the baseline for a given TN and TP load as

\[ \Delta_{biomass\%} = \frac{sensitivity_i * 100\%}{baseline} \]

where \(\Delta_{biomass}\) is the relative change in biomass, baseline is the baseline biomass, and sensitivityi is the biomass for a given parameter in the sensitivity analysis.

In addition, I calculated which parameter results in the maximum change in biomass relative to the baseline. It is important to note that this doesn’t tell us the direction of change just the magnitude of change.
